title: How This AI Startup Grew by 100x in Just 6 Months | Fireworks AI, Lin Qiao
description:
Fireworks AI is one of the fastest growing AI startup in the industry. Over the past six months, Fireworks AI has experienced a 100x increase in traffic. Also in July, the company successfully closed a Series B funding round led by Sequoia, bringing its valuation to $552 million.

Lin Qiao, who previously served as the Head of PyTorch, shares how her experiences there inspired the creation of Fireworks AI. In this video, she discusses the ongoing AI transformation and offers insights into what it takes to excel as a software engineer in this rapidly evolving landscape.

title: Early Uber investor's bootcamp for VC | Paul Bragiel, 101 Fellowship
description:
We're thrilled to welcome back Paul Bragiel from Golden Gate Ventures. Paul is recognized as a legendary investor, having been an early investor in Uber, Stripes, and Zappos. Heâ€™s also a serial entrepreneur with three startup experiences under his belt. Paul was an angel investor in the early days of Uber, earning over 2000 times his investment. In this video, Paul shares his insights on what makes a great investor and a great entrepreneur, and he brings an exciting fellowship opportunity for those aspiring to become VCs.

title: What It Takes to Reach $100M+ Revenue as a Startup | CircleCI
description:
CircleCIâ€™s CEO, Jim Rose, and CTO, Rob Zuber, sit down to discuss a few of the lessons learned as they grew CircleCI to $100M+ in revenue. In this video, they share insights about how to build a winning team, the key to finding and keeping product-market fit, and what it takes to future-proof your business against new technology like Generative AI. While the risk for startups is high, there are many ways SaaS platforms can stay ahead of the competition to come out on top.

title: How I Built $825M Email Revolution Called Superhuman | Rahul Vohra
description:
Superhuman's CEO, Rahul, reveals his thrilling journey of growing his startup into a company valued at $825M. In this interview, Rahul explains in detail the core strategies that allowed him to secure a unique position while competing with tech giants like Gmail and Outlook. The interview covers everything from the secrets behind finding product-market fit (PMF) that led to explosive growth, to the behind-the-scenes story of how they continually grew while maintaining user love. His practical advice for first-time founders and aspiring entrepreneurs is sure to inspire many. This interview uncovers all the secrets behind how Rahul's Superhuman was able to revolutionize email services and achieve success.

title: First Lesson Taught in Harvard MBA in 18 Minutes | Thales Teixeira
description:
Today's video features Thales S. Teixeira, V. Associate Professor at the University of California. Previously, he taught students at Harvard Business School for over 10 years. In his book, he explains how existing businesses can identify points where they fail to create value and offers methods to provide high value to customers. He examines the customer value chain, proposing a framework to identify and break apart the weakest link. He teaches how to generate ideas that offer high value to customers and how to attract customers away from established players with those ideas.

To purchase his book: https://a.co/d/hkoaHzs

â€œOne of the simplest and most useful exercises that psychotherapy has gifted to us is known as the Empty Chair Technique. A client who has been wrestling with their feelings towards someone is gently requested to stop discussing them in the third person and is instead invited to face a chair and start talking to this bit of furniture as if there were on it â€“ to all intents â€“ the specific troubling person in their life, perhaps a long dead absent father, a neglectful mother or a traitorous so-called friendâ€¦â€

description:
Enjoying our Youtube videos? Get full access to all our audio content, videos, and thousands of thought-provoking articles, conversation cards and more with The School of Life Subscription: https://t.ly/pAp30

Learn, heal and grow. Get the best of The School of Life delivered straight to your inbox: https://t.ly/SAMBZ

FURTHER READING

You can read more on this and other subjects in our articles, here: https://t.ly/Z8GWC

â€œFor some of us, our lives are guided â€“ and hemmed in â€“ by one overwhelming imperative: we must never let people down. Not just a few friends and family members, but pretty much anyone who wants anything of us. Perhaps someone wants to see us again for supper. We kept them entertained and now they want more. The problem is that we really donâ€™t much like them â€“ but we go anyway, because how could we not, next time and probably the twenty times after that. We give money to people we donâ€™t trust, we stay up too late at parties we hate, we wind up on holiday with characters we have little in common with. We would feel a sense of obligation to someoneâ€¦â€

title: On Feeling Painfully Different  #short  #individual  #different
description:
Much is said about the virtues and pleasures of individuality but let's also admit to how frankly lonely and frightening it can be to find ourselves (yet again) in a peculiar minority, where the differences between us and others strike us as bewildering rather than emboldening, how do we alleviate these isolating thoughts?

Enjoying our YouTube videos? Get full access to all our audio content, videos, and thousands of thought-provoking articles, conversation cards and more with The School of Life Subscription: https://bit.ly/4cWPq6D


Learn, heal and grow; get the best of The School of Life delivered straight to your inbox:
https://bit.ly/4aVl6r3

FURTHER READING

You can read more on this and other subjects in our articles, here: https://bit.ly/4aBcjuB

â€œMuch is said about the virtues and pleasures of individuality â€“ of being someone who stands out from the crowd and delights in their particularity. But letâ€™s also admit to how frankly lonely and frightening it can be to find ourselves (yet again) in a peculiar minority, where the differences between us and others strike us as bewildering rather than emboldening, when for example:
â€” Everyone wants to gossip but we prefer generosity and forgiveness.
â€” Everyone is at ease but weâ€™re melancholy and self-conscious.
â€” Everyone is cheerful but we canâ€™t let go of anxiety and apprehension.â€

title: Managing your Mood: Tips for Staying Present | The School of Life
description:
Why is it so hard to regulate your emotions? Learn how to stay in tune with your mood and embrace emotional fluctuations.  
 
Read our article, â€˜We are made of moodsâ€™ to find out more about your changing emotional states: https://t.ly/lfggR


Our moods are affected by the smallest of changes â€“ from fluctuations in our blood sugar content and serotonin levels, to whether or not our partner gave us a kiss before we left for work. In turn, our emotions condition almost every aspect of our behaviour: how we respond to events, react to challenges, and feel about ourselves. Understanding just how powerfully our emotional state impacts our thoughts and actions can help us manage those effects more readily â€“ and build a more stable and forgiving relationship with ourselves.

We are a passionate group of people on a mission to bring about healing, growth, calm and self-understanding. 
 
We derive our ideas from psychology, psychotherapy, philosophy, art and culture. As our name â€“ The School of Life â€“ suggests, we are here to teach people how life can be lived and what can make it truly worthwhile, effective and fulfilling.

title: Are you afraid of intimacy? #animation #shorts  #intimacy
description:
Sometimes we may end up in a couple where we spend a lot of time complaining - to concerned friends and family - that the other person is evidently and committedly â€˜afraid of intimacy.â€™ They donâ€™t often talk of their emotions; they may find it hard to be physically cosy; they donâ€™t cry so often.

â€œSometimes we may end up in a couple where we spend a lot of time complaining â€“ to concerned friends and family â€“ that the other person is evidently and committedly â€˜afraid of intimacy.â€™ They donâ€™t often talk of their emotions; they may find it hard to be physically cosy; they donâ€™t cry so often. 
Whereas we on the other hand â€“ as all our acquaintances know â€“ are the emotionally fluent ones. We long to be close to someone, we long to discuss our feelings openly and without restraint, we are healthy and ready for love. title: The Number One Rule for Healthy Relationships
description:
In relationships, honesty is key. Learn how to say what you truly feel by following this one simple rule.

â€œAs we know only too well, becoming an adult has very little to do with turning 18 or 22, driving a car or being entitled to drink, getting a mortgage or having a child. An adulthood worthy of the name is an internal process which may post-date the acquisition of a formal adult identity by many years. We might be 92 and still, very slowly, leaving adolescence behind. title: Things You Have to Forget in Order to Live
description:
Enjoying our Youtube videos? Get full access to all our audio content, videos, and thousands of thought-provoking articles, conversation cards and more with The School of Life Subscription: https://t.ly/o2Ko1

Learn, heal and grow. Get the best of The School of Life delivered straight to your inbox: https://t.ly/fLL3V

FURTHER READING

You can read more on this and other subjects in our articles, here: https://www.theschooloflife.com/articles/

â€œ(1)We tend to imagine that in order to live a good life, we need to have to have an appetite for the truth. 

(2)But what if, in reality, in order to keep going and get anything done, we actually need to blind ourselves to a range of realities and have to swallow a number of illusions without which we couldnâ€™t possibly have the willpower to continue. 

(3)Here are some of the blind spots necessary to our flourishing.

(4)First and foremost, we need to pretend that weâ€™re not going to die and therefore have to convince ourselves that all the things we fervently trust are so important and so urgent, really do matter and wonâ€™t look like incomprehensible, futile mulch within a hundred years or less.

(5)We have to care manically about what â€˜othersâ€™ think - though they hardly give us a thought, let alone a fair one.

(6)We have to imagine that we could (one day) be loved and understood - though few things are, in fact, ever more in doubt.

(7)We have to stay on our side - though we know, in our hearts, how beastly and strange we really are.

(8)We have to melt at the cuteness of small children - though we know how most of them will turn out and that the world weâ€™re teaching them about doesnâ€™t really exist.

(9)We have to look forward to the next few years with excitement - though almost every new day is a scratchy six or below.

(10)We have to believe that weâ€™re collectively making progress - though every invention unleashes a necessary set of appalling unintended consequences.

(11)We have to care about humanity - though most of its members are insufferable from close up.

(12)We have to look forward to the future - though if we had a chance to learn what fate had in store, we almost certainly would not want to know.

(13)We have to keep being excited about buying things - though we know how seldom any of them make a difference.

(14)We have to keep going travelling - though being somewhere else is always better in memory or anticipation.

(15)We have to keep seeing our so-called friends - though we would be crushed by hearing a fraction of what really goes through their minds.

(16)We have to believe in a comfortable, wise old age - though it will mostly be agony, aches and catheters.

(17)We have to not properly notice how beautiful, interesting and opportunity-filled life is - in case we were to go mad from excitement and regret.

(18)In short, letâ€™s not fool ourselves that we really want to know the full truth. We require only so much of it as is compatible with making it out of bed. We have to confront an uncomfortable fact about self-awareness: those who most know how to enjoy life may also be those who - at points - are masters at fruitfully lying to themselves.â€

â€œThere is one question that, perhaps more than any other, gets to the root of who we are and what motivates us:
                    
          What did I need to do in childhood to win the support and approval of my parents?

We might - to sharpen the picture - need to lean on a few subsidiary enquiries:

To please my father, I needed toâ€¦
To please my mother, I needed toâ€¦

Not to upset my mother, I needed toâ€¦
Not to upset my father, I needed toâ€¦

Whatever might be claimed, no family ever gives its offspring unconditional love; there is always, more or less subtly, something that one has to do and to be - and other things that must at all costs be skirtedâ€¦â€

Hi Friends!
I just got back from travel last week and needed some time to recharge and reset. My favorite thing after a long trip is just to come back to the basics of doing my own laundry, cooking my own meal and meeting friends. Can you relate? It truly feels like summer in California and I am here for it, I tried to make the most out of it and enjoy it out and about. This vlog felt like a very chatty catch up vlog, let me know if you enjoyed this type of video!

Much Love,

Sanne

Japan Diaries: A Week in Tokyo & Osaka, Vintage Shopping & Matcha Pop Up!
description:
Japan Diaries: A Week in Tokyo & Osaka, 24h trip to Haneda, Vintage Shopping & Matcha Pop Up!

Hi friends!

Apologies for the later post this weekâ€”I had to finish some final edits after we returned from our trip! Editing travel vlogs is always my favorite because there's so much fun footage to work with. This weekâ€™s video takes you along for a week in Japan. Max and I are spending our final week here, and itâ€™s been incredibly exciting. Weâ€™re here for a mix of work and fun because weâ€™re launching our very first Nekohama Matcha Pop-Up in Osaka. Weâ€™ve been working really hard on this, and itâ€™s been truly special to bring our matcha back to Japan. The feedback has been absolutely incredible so thankyou so much.

During the meet-up, I had the pleasure of meeting a few of you, and it was so lovely to spend time together. To everyone who gave me thoughtful gifts and lettersâ€”thank you so much! ILY forever!

In case you missed the pop-up or are planning to visit Osaka soon, the pop-up will be at MIXUP at W Osaka until September 31st. Be sure to make a reservation, as it can get busy!

It truly felt like we got a taste of living in Japan for a little while, which was so special. I hope you enjoyed this vlog, and Iâ€™ll see you next week in L.A.

Much love,

Sanne

title: Are We Moving? | Coffee Talks in Tokyo
description:
Coffee Talks | Travel Routines, Practicing Self-Love & Are We Moving?

Hi,

How are you? I hope you are having a wonderful Saturday. I am currently in Osaka and filmed a little coffee talk video in Tokyo. I really enjoy these videos and I enjoyed this one especially as I spend a little alone time in the city. Tokyo is truly one of my favorite cities, it feels so safe and clean there is so many fun cafes, good restaurant and hidden shopping places. 

I guess this video is more of " pick in my brain" video and wanted to share where my head is at lately. While I travel I find it sometimes hard to slow dine and tune in with myself but when I do, oh wonders happen!

How are you dealing with self-love? is it something you practice or does it come naturally to you?

X
Sanne

title: what I eat in a day in japan | bento box & street food in osaka!
description:
what I eat in a day in japan | bento box while traveling & come to the osaka streetfood market with me.

Hi everyone,

Happy Saturday! I hope you're having a wonderful weekend. I'm writing this caption from Tokyo, where Max and I arrived a week ago for a very special project!

I just recovered from a bad cold, which kept me from creating the vlog exactly how I wanted. Despite this, I still wanted to upload a video for you today. Please excuse my voice and some rough audio in parts of the video.

I am so excited to finally announce that Nekohama is collaborating with W Osaka for a matcha pop-up! After so much hard work, it's incredibly special to bring Nekohama back to its origin, Japan. Together with the executive pastry chef, we've created some delicious matcha pastries and drinks that will be available for the next two months in Osaka. If you're traveling there, be sure to visit!

If you want to come say hi for our pop up launch event on August 3rd in Osaka, Max and I will be there! 

Date: Saturday August 3rd
Time: 3-5 PM
Location: MIXUP at W Hotel in Osaka

title: Ghalib Suleiman - Open Q&A. YOUR Questions Answered
description:
Ghalib Suleiman joins us to answer YOUR data-related questions.

Drop your questions in the comments and we'll answer them live on the show.

title: Andrew Ng - Why Data Engineering is Critical to Data-Centric AI
description: Andrew Ng is a pioneer in machine learning and AI. He joins us to discuss why data engineering is critical to data-centric AI.

title: Tevje Olin - What Should Data Engineers Focus On?
description:
Should data engineers focus on the technology? Finding ways to transform data into something valuable? Both?

Tevje Olin joins us to chat about what he thinks data engineers should focus on.

title: Rob Harmon - Small Data, Efficiency, and Data Modeling
description: Rob Harmon joins us to chat about small data, being efficient, data modeling, and much more.

title: Joe Reis & Matt Housley - The Return of the Show!
description: We're back from our Summer break and ready to rant about all kinds of stuff. We talk about the tech downturn, AI hype bubbles, and much more.

title: Nick Schrock and Wes McKinney - Composable Data Stacks, Open Table Formats, and More
description: Nick Schrock and Wes McKinney join us for a chat about composable data stacks, open table formats, managing complexity, and much more.

title: Summer Break 2024 Episode + Zhamak Dehghani
description:
Joe and Matt are going to take the summer off from the Monday Morning Data Chat. They'll chat about what's on their minds, summer plans, and more.

Plus, special guest Zhamak Dehghani discusses the current state of Data Mesh, and what she's up to at NextData.

title: Chris Tabb - Platform Gravity & Combining App, Data, and Algorithms
description: Chris Tabb joins us to chat about something on his mind - platform gravity. The direction seems be the unified platform that combines applications, data, and algorithms. Chris is here to shed light on this trend.

title: Ghalib Suleiman - The Zero-Interest Rate Hangover in Data and AI
description: Ghalib Suleiman (Polytomic) joins the show to chat how the zero-interest rate hangover is affecting data and AI. We dive into the AI hype cycle, "data influencers", data vendors, data teams, and much more.

title: Bart Vandekerckhove - Data Security Deep Dive
description: Bart Vandekerckhove (Raito) joins us to chat about data security, and the challenges data teams face when using traditional IAM technology and workflows for data access/security management.

title: Yali Sassoon - Using LLMs to Support the Analytics Workflow
description:
It seems like LLMs are taking the analytics world by storm. But how do you use them to support the analytics workflow? 

Yali Sassoon (CTO, Co-founder of Snowplow) joins us to chat about this and much more. We'll also likely dive into behavioral analytics and more.

Snowplow: https://snowplow.io/

title: David Yaffe & John Kutay - The State of Streaming and CDC
description:
David Yaffe (Estuary) and John Kutay (Striim) join the show to chat about the state of streaming and change data capture (CDC) in 2024 and beyond. There is a lot to cover and learn in this show.

Estuary: https://estuary.dev/
Striim: https://www.striim.com/

#dataengineering #data #ai

title: Solomon Kahn - Customer-Facing Data Products
description:
Data products are all the rage. But what are they? And what the heck does "customer-facing" mean? Will your old-school BI tool handle customer-facing needs?

Solomon Kahn joins us to chat about customer-facing data products and much more. He's one of the people we consider to be at the bleeding edge of modern analytics and data products, so definitely check this out.

Delivery Layer: https://www.deliverylayer.com/
LinkedIn: https://www.linkedin.com/in/solomonkahn/

title: Katharine Jarmul - Are We Solving the "Right" Problems with AI?
description:
Katharine Jarmul is a AI/ML privacy and security expert, and the author of Practical Data Privacy. She joins us to chat about whether we are solving the "right" problems with AI/ML/data science, exploring what "safe", "responsible", and "ethical" AI means, and much more.

LinkedIn: https://www.linkedin.com/in/katharinejarmul/
Twitter: https://twitter.com/kjam?lang=en
Probably Private (newsletter): https://probablyprivate.com/
Practical Data Privacy: https://learning.oreilly.com/library/view/practical-data-privacy/9781098129453/

title: Matt Turck - The 2024 MAD Landscape (Special Show)
description: Matt Turck joins us for a special chat about the newly released 2024 MAD (ML, AI, and Data) Landscape. There's a TON happening at light speed in the AI and data space right now, and Matt and the FirstMark crew have done a phenomenal job keeping a pulse on things.

title: Deadly Beauty: Why Everyone Feels Ugly Now
description:
If youâ€™re struggling, consider therapy with BetterHelp #ad. Click  https://betterhelp.com/elizabethfilips for a 10% discount on your first month of therapy with acredentialed professional specific to your needs ğŸ’š

Itâ€™s hard to be beautiful today, but the sad truth is: it never was much easier. Iâ€™ve been always obsessed with what determines beauty, and have always been interested in the interpretations (and misinterpretations) of evolutionary psychology, modern psychology, anthropology and medicine. I never knew however, just how much economics and politics had to do with it, how much health and disease, money and the church affected what we now consider beautiful or ugly. And even more so, just how much our perceived looks can affect our life. I spent months and months researching and reading about this, satisfying all the curiosities Iâ€™ve had since being a little girl and confusions I still had on just how and why we treat each other and ourselves the way we do. I really hope this gives some information and help to any younger version of Elizabeth out there. 

The second half of the video (timestamped below) is focused mainly on obesity: something Iâ€™m also very passionate about as a soon to be (in a few weeks eeeeek) doctor. I think thereâ€™s so much gaslighting in modern body positivity and so much that remains unsaid but definitely felt and experienced by people everywhere. It might be a bit of a stronger take - but I hope it makes sense! 

I ended up having 135 citations for this video. I worked on it all myself, and this video kind of got out of control from the amount of things I ended up reading and referencing - so reflecting my chaotic mind, I tried my best to keep the citations as clean as possible, but I do apologise if thereâ€™s any repetitions or messy links. The full list was too long for the description, so Iâ€™ve linked a page below with all the books/links/studies referenced. The easiest thing to do is to look at the number of the citation on the video (the rest of the text might be too small in the end for a phone screen) and refer to the page for an easy copy paste if you want to check them out! 

A lot of the historical information was new to me, and I tried my best to find accurate resources and to double and triple check them and go as far back as I could to the original sources - but where thereâ€™s mistakes in what I say in the video, I do apologise and welcome the corrections! 

For a full list of the citations shown (it might be easier to look at the citation number in the video and reference it here): https://www.elizabethfilips.com/post/citations-why-you-will-never-be-beautiful

title: The Complex Psychology of Why Everyone Quits the Gym
description:
Check my Copilot link to get 14 days free with your own personal trainer! https://go.mycopilot.com/elizabeth-filips 
To get a free summary of the book I mentioned, Algorithms to live by - Brian Christian, you can use my link here: http://shortform.com/elizabeth
As a recently-reformed, professional gym-quitter, Iâ€™ve tried everything under the sun for 10 years to try and get myself motivated to work out. And always failed. 10 months into my newfound gym consistency and exercise enjoyment, I re-approached the psychological theories of behavioural change and execise enoyment with a fresh eye (and patience), and summarised the main learning points here. I hope they help explain why quitting the gym is so easy (beyond the usual suspects of laziness and self-hatred) and why quitting, in the case of exercise, might be more of a rational choice than we think. Hope anything here helps for any sort of new habit or behaviour you want to create!

title: Why You Always Quit the Gym: the Science of Enjoying Exercise
description:
Click my CoPilot link https://go.mycopilot.com/ElizabethFilips to get a FREE TRIAL with your own expert fitness and health coach ğŸ’ª
If you need a summary of how un-fit and how much I've always hated exercise: I can't even ride a bike. I always HATED having to move one more step than I strictly need to, I never saw the point or pleasure in voluntarily running on the spot when I could much rather spend that time reading, watching or painting something. And so, it's no surprise that the accumulated uselessness and hatred for working out lead to years of trying to be healthier but always just quitting the gym. For the first time in my life, I've managed to be consistent and actually enjoy exercise with the help and guidance of my personal trainer, so whether or not you can get one too, here's everything mine taught me and all the ways she changed my attitude and behaviours towards exercise.

title: we're no different.
description:
a story about two generations, transcending through time. 



Meet Shaun Evaristo, a living legend in the dance world whose steps have echoed through time, shaping the rhythm and soul of the entertainment industry. With a career spanning decades, Shaun has not only danced alongside the greats but has himself become a cornerstone for aspiring dancers. His influence is a tapestry woven into the fabric of dance history.

As the spotlight shifts with the arrival of newer generations, Shaun faces the inevitable challenge of time. The industry that once felt like home now whispers of change, and the voice of a younger generation grows louder. It's a crossroads that tests the essence of his passion, pushing him to confront the reality that perhaps his moment in the limelight has dimmed.

Enter Sean Lew, a force from a younger generation. Amidst his ambition, Sean carries a profound respect for the path paved by legends like Shaun. In Sean's eyes, Shaun's legacy is not a relic of the past but a beacon guiding the future of dance. 
But as Sean navigates his own journey towards greatness, his relentless pursuit of perfection begins to cast a shadow over his joy. Caught in the whirlwind of ambition, he loses sight of the essence that first drew him to dance.

It's within this shared space of dreams and doubts that Shaun and Sean forge an unlikely bond. Shaun, with the wisdom of experience, becomes a mentor and a friend to Sean, reminding him that the art of dance is as much about the soul as it is about the steps. Together, they embark on a journey that transcends generations, reminding each other and the world that while the dance may change, the passion that fuels it remains eternal.



directed by: Sean Lew
creative directed: Zev York 
choreography by: Shaun Evaristo & Sean Lew 
edited by: Zev York 
filmed by: Vibrvncy, Gerald Nononato, Jon Shih, Kai Goh, John Kim
performed by: Shaun Evaristo & Sean Lew
stage: Good Times by The Company

title: 100 Bad Days - AJR | Sean Lew Choreography | Flip The Switch 2023
description:
i didn't know if i was going to actually teach this or not... 

four days before this event, i was in Poland, sitting in the lobby across from Kaycee, deciding what i was going to teach. and with everything going on, I didn't have any time to really prepare a piece, so i thought i would just choose one of my older pieces. But teaching for me, is a very sacred experience for me, especially in LA. 

So i looked at Kaycee and just said 'F**K IT. we are in such a moment of our lives, where we are working so hard and have so much going on, and i'm sure so many other people feel the same. i just want people to understand that being the best at anything is NOT the most important thing. finding the joy and happiness throughout the process is what's important.' 

i will FOREVER cherish classes like these because i get to watch so many dancers smile with each other, mess up with each other, laugh with each other, cheer each other on. THAT is dance. THAT is community. THAT is life. 

so this piece is reminder for people like us who work so hard, that we forget to play hard too... 


Thank you Alex and Jasmine for the incredible event and for having me. 
Thank you Vibrvncy for the impeccable captures. 
Thank you Kaycee for the forever golden moments that I always cherish. 



Danced by: Kaycee Rice & Sean Lew 
Choreography: Sean Lew
Filmed by: Gerald Nonato, Kai Goh
Event: Flip The Switch (Los Angeles)

description:

library(patchwork)
library(ggplot2)

p1 = ggplot(mtcars) + 
  geom_point(aes(mpg, wt)) + 
  ggtitle("Plot 1")
p1
p2 = ggplot(mtcars) + 
  geom_boxplot(aes(gear, disp, group=gear)) + 
  ggtitle("Plot 2")
p2
p3 = ggplot(mtcars) + 
  geom_point(aes(hp, wt, color=mpg)) + 
  ggtitle("Plot 3")
p3

  geom_bar(aes(gear)) + 
  facet_wrap(~cyl) + 
  ggtitle("Plot 4")
p4

p1 + p2
p1 + p2 + p3 + p4 
p1 + p2 + p3 + p4 + 
  plot_layout(nrow=3, byrow=FALSE)
p1 + p2 + p3 + p4 + 
  plot_layout(widths=c(2, 1))
p1 + p2 + p3 + p4 + 
  plot_layout(widths=c(2, 1), heights=c(5, 1))
p1 / p2
p1 | (p2 / p3)
p1 + (p2 / p3)
(p1 | (p2 / p3)) + 
  plot_annotation(
    title="The surprising truth about cars",
    subtitle="3 plots will reveal secrets about cars",
    caption="Source: patchwork package in R"
  )
p1 + p2 + p3 + 
  plot_annotation(tag_levels="I")
(p1 + p2) / p3 + 
  plot_annotation(tag_levels="A")

library(grid)
p1 + textGrob("Negative Relationship!!!")

library(gridExtra)
p1 + gtableGrob(mtcars[1:10, c("mpg", "wt")])
